    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Can the President Come Out and Play?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Russell McCulley letter on Sept 26 article defends keeping part of Pennsylvania Avenue in front of White House closed to cars; drawing</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I applaud the efforts of Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan and others to revitalize Pennsylvania Avenue in Washington (''Senator and Delegate Back Plan to Reopen Pennsylvania Avenue,'' news article, Sept. 26).</p>
        <p>But I fail to see how closing the short segment in front of the White House to cars for security reasons presents a threat, as Bob Dole put it, to ''fundamental American values, such as openness and accessibility.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I applaud the efforts of Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan and others to revitalize Pennsylvania Avenue in Washington (''Senator and Delegate Back Plan to Reopen Pennsylvania Avenue,'' news article, Sept. 26).</p>
        <p>But I fail to see how closing the short segment in front of the White House to cars for security reasons presents a threat, as Bob Dole put it, to ''fundamental American values, such as openness and accessibility.''</p>
        <p>To the contrary: I recently spent part of a pleasant afternoon in the area in question, along with many  skateboarders, roller-hockey players and tourists -- all of us enjoying an open and accessible view of the White House and unencumbered by the havoc of 29,000 cars a day and the ''tour buses that once idled there.''</p>
        <p>What could be more fundamentally American than that?</p>
        <p>RUSSELL MCCULLEY  New Orleans, Sept. 26, 2000</p>
      </block>
